options.tex:
\begin{align}
P(H\vert Y) &= 0.28 \\ 
P(H\vert D) &= 0.3 \\
P(Y\vert H) &= ?
\end{align}

reason.tex:
\begin{align} P(Y\vert H) &= \underbrace{\dfrac{P(H\vert Y)\cdot P(Y)}{P(H)}}_{\text{Bayes' Theorem}} \\ &= \dfrac{P(H\vert Y)\cdot P(Y)}{P(H\vert Y)\cdot P(Y) + P(H\vert D)\cdot P(D)} \\ \end{align} \\ %text Now, a patient is \underline{\text{equally likely}} to pick either yoga or the drug. Hence, $P(Y) = P(D) = \frac{1}{2}$. % \begin{align} P(Y\vert H) &= \dfrac{0.28\times 0.5}{0.28\times 0.5 + 0.3\times 0.5} = \frac{14}{29} \end{align}\\ %text Now, notice that $\frac{14}{29}\lt 50\%$. Hence, if a patient has a heart attack, then it is \underline{\text{less likely}} that he did yoga. Which means, that he is more likely to have taken the drug.
\underline{\text{But still, he had a heart attack.}}
Hence, doing yoga would have reduced the chances of a heart attack still further. %
